Here's what's gonna happen when the Federal Reserve raises the interest rate
The interest rate will increase and the bull market (growing market) will stumble, the return on bonds will increase and the economy will go into recession.
That's what we know.
What we do not know is how long it will happen and how long it will last.
In economics, history provides little indication of time frame..
After the first increase would interest rate, the recession occurred in just 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The aggression of the Federal Reserve to increase interest rates is often, though not always, a determining factor in how the economy and financial assets respond.
Therefore, U.S. central bank officials have stressed so strongly that investors should not focus on when they start to increase the interest rate but on the trajectory of the time needed for normalisation.
Indeed, there are multiple variables in the game.
However, in the end, market players may find that all the agitation over the interest rate increase has been exaggerated.
"The first interest rate increase decided by the Fed after the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some voices as a sign of the "cheap money" era," said Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, in a note to customers.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal but still small levels to constitute the seismic shock that everyone seems to be afraid of.
However, it cannot be said that there will be no effects.
Here is how several sectors of the economy could react, based on historical trends:
Given the situation faced by the market in recent months, anticipation of the interest rate increase may volatilise things for a while.
But at the time of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
"There seems to be a tendency for the return on capital to stall for 12-24 months after the first increase, which may reflect the phase in monetary policy again," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what will happen after the Fed increases.
More specifically, in the last 35 years, the market has grown sharply - by about 14 percent - towards interest rate growth, quite invariable in the 250 days period after (average climb of 2.6%) after which it returns to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the last six cycles of 14.4%, according to a recent analysis published on Barron by the chief strategist of Nuveen Asset Management.
Deutsche said that the impact on the shares tends to become more pronounced later in the interest rate growth cycle and benefits begin to decline.
The recession is a reality of economic life but interest rate growth often contributes to it.
In the current situation, the Fed is facing conditions that did not exist before and could speed up a recession.
Specifically, gross domestic product will approach its historic minimum point for a Fed interest rate increase.
According to Deutsche Bank, out of the 118 interest rate increases after 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was less than 4.5%.
Even though in the second quarter of 2015 the value was 3.6%, few expect the situation to persist, with the third quarter reaching only 1.5%, according to the Atlanta Fed.
The interest rate increase in such a fragile economy could be risky and could raise the question "if this time it is different," Deutsche said.
Market players have been preparing all year for a growth decision from the Fed, with all eyes aimed towards this week's meeting of the Federal Open Market Commission, which ends on Thursday.
Although many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an increase in the interest rate during this meeting, short-term transactions indicate a probability of only 25%.
"In our study conducted after 1950, all interest rate growth cycles to date have been in a super cycle of profit growth, with GDP eclipsing peaks before the recession very quickly after recovery began," the report said.
On the contrary, this was a strangely slow recovery after the worst recession in the period under review.
The current cycle is by far the longest expected by the Fed since the end of the last recession; the record had been 35 months, and it reached 74 months and continues.
Fixed income was also volatile given that the market anticipates an increase in the interest rate and the pattern is somewhat similar to that of dividends.
The main difference is that the impact is faster on bonds than on shares when the Fed changes policy.
In the case of bonds, it appears that the benefits change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease of the cycle occurs.
At the end of the interest rate cycle, the return on bonds decreases immediately," Deutsche said.
Charles Schwab strategies believe that these interest rate increases will bring profitability closer between short-term and long-term bonds, flattening the curve.
High-efficiency bonds do better in such an environment, although "we are still cautious about forcing profitability," said Kathy Jones, a fixed income analyst within Schwab.
Interestingly, Jones believes that markets have already adapted to the expectations of Fed policy.
"In addition to the power of the dollar and the decline in estimated inflation, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of a more rigorous monetary policy," Jones wrote.
Short-term interest rates have increased, the profitability curve is fairer, the spread of the average credit interest rate has expanded and volatility has increased - all market characteristics when the Fed tightens policy.
Overall, companies operating mostly in the US will benefit from the interest rate increase and local products will become more attractive.
High-debt multinationals will suffer because the increase in the dollar will lead to the increase in their products in the global market space and their debt will be more expensive.
"History shows that "quality" stocks tend to be more profitable in the three months following an initial interest rate increase," said analyst Goldman Sachs in a report to customers.
Firms with strong balance sheets exceeded those with a poor balance after each of the 1994, 1999 and 2004 interest rate increases by an average of 5 percentage points.
Companies with high capital and low volatility stocks also exceeded similar companies with a low quality, by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) respectively.
Duty will become an important matter.
Companies with a high percentage of floating debt have the most to lose, Goldman says.
Consumers will also benefit from the increase in the dollar.
Those who save could also benefit, although experts disagree about how quickly this will happen.
