PHE published the "reference" report last month and described it as a "complex analysis of evidence."
Several researchers, however, questioned the robustness of the data and pointed to links between certain experts and the tobacco industry.
An article published last month in the medical journal Lancet attacked the "extraordinarily fragile base" on which PHE founded its main conclusion.
Two other researchers writing in the BMJ questioned their claims and foundation "on solid ground or on quicksand".
Martin McKee, Professor of European Public Health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, Professor of Clinical Epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, stated: "A fundamental principle of public health is that policies must be based on evidence of effectiveness."
They said they expected that PHE claims that "current estimates show that electronic cigarettes are 95% less harmful than smoking" are based on a detailed analysis of evidence and models.
In reality, a single meeting attended by 12 people led to the development of a multi-criteria decision analysis model (MCDA) summarizing their views on the negative effects associated with various nicotine-containing products; the results of this meeting were briefly presented in a research paper.
McKee and Capewell claimed that one of the sponsors of the meeting was a company titled EuroSwiss Health, whose chief executive was said to have received funding in the past from British American Tobacco for conducting an independent study.
It also validated BAT accreditation in public health in a sustainability report, he said.
They added that one of the 12 participants in the meeting said funding received from an electronic cigarette manufacturer but not funding that is reported to have been received from the cigarette and tobacco manufacturing company, Philip Morris International.
No arguments were provided on the basis of which panel members were selected but among them are some known "frontiers" in electronic cigarette production, some of whom even declare industry funding in the paper.
Other meeting participants are not known for their tobacco control expertise.
The meeting was also attended by the head of the PHE tobacco control section.
The group's elaborate research work "convincingly obscures" the fact that there is "solid evidence missing about the harmful effect most products have according to most criteria", McKee and Capewell said.
However, none of these links or limitations are mentioned in the PHE report.
McKee and Capewell have stated that PHE claims that "so far there is no evidence that electronic cigarettes constitute a factor encouraging smoking among children or non-smokers" are premature.
Professor Kevin Fenton, director of the health department at PHE, says that there has been a response in the past to claims in BMJ.
He said, "Electronic cigarettes are significantly less harmful than smoking"
One in two people who have smoked their whole lives loses their lives because of this addiction.
All evidence suggests that the risk of e-cigarettes for health is comparatively minor, but we need to continue to study the long-term effects.
The EHP has a clear duty to inform the public about the information that arises and that does not arise from the evidence, especially in view of the high degree of public confusion about the relative dangers compared to tobacco.
Annually, about 80,000 people lose their lives due to a disease associated with smoking and the annual costs incurred by the national health system due to smoking reach £2 billion.
Clearly expressing the current evidence - namely that while the use of electronic cigarettes is not without risks, it only presents a fraction of the harmful effect of smoking - we are fulfilling our national duty.
