Violinist David Grimal: There were no world tours in Bach's era.
Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were working people, artists and not commercial representatives.
French violinist David Grimal is one of the great artists of our time, known not only as a soloist but also as the initiator of a less common project, quite "strange", as he himself says, Les Dissonances - an orchestra made up of international soloists and talented musicians, who perform a symphonic repertoire without having a conductor, and that makes it at least a curiosity in the classical music landscape.
Les Dissonances was this year at the Enescu Festival with two performances: a performance on Sunday, where the soloist was David Grimal, the founder of the orchestra, and one Monday, when the cellist Xavier Phillips was at the forefront, the works composed by Enescu being inexhaustible.
Both performances, performed on the stage of the Athenaeum, showed the public a different way of performing classical music.
Les Dissonances appeared on the music scene in 2004 being, at the time, the only classical musical ensemble in which there was no conductor.
The conductor is the most important musician for musicians.
It is true, on the one hand musicians need an education either to become soloists or to become performers in an orchestra - talk of instrumentalists, and not composers.
They're formed as "specialized workers."
They think they need a conductor.
On the other side of the stage, for the public, all musical fetishization focuses on the conductor.
And so, the business, the music industry, does its marketing.
Therefore, we are no longer talking about music.
So if we look at this world, we have skilled workers on the one hand, which is stupid, and an audience that can't listen, but has to watch, which is stupid again," David Grimal considered.
The violinist recounts that this change in the way he makes music came from the "musical deceptions" of his career as a soloist.
I was like a high-level athlete who had to do the same exercise around the world with different orchestras, to make a lot of money and bring money to the music industry.
Ten years ago, when I was about 30 years old, I found this very depressing, because I no longer found creativity and human brotherhood in this system.
So, I found no point in continuing on this road.
So I decided to create Les Dissonances.
This happened in 2004, and at the time no one did this without a conductor: "The musical world, extremely conservative, did not want such projects."
"How do you imagine doing marketing with a collective of musicians in which there is no ego anymore?" asks the artist.
David Grimal admits that Les Dissonaces represents "a luxury", stating that none of the musicians who are part of the orchestra depends on the success of this project to live.
In 10 years of the existence of the ensemble, the lack of a conductor has not proved to be a hindrance in the musical act: " Curiously, the more complex we play a repertoire, the simpler it seems, because all musicians are obliged to be present in the opera and not just in the role", Grimal said, adding that at the Sunday show "we were 74 conductors on stage".
In Grimal's view, the Enescu Festival is a "very brave" one, precisely because it invited Les Dissonances: "An extraordinary festival, where the world's largest orchestras are present and 3 times a day, and in the midst of these orchestras you also invited this strange group".
In a temple of orchestral tradition, such as the Enescu Festival, there was place and interest for something different, which breaks barriers.
Speaking of Enescu's work, the violinist admits to feeling the Romanian music of the famous Romanian composer, so he did not need a special approach when he introduced works by Enescu in his repertoire.
Grimal notes that Enescu's music is very instinctive, but this is what happens when we talk about George Enescu and Romanian music, "because there is also a George Enescu who made French music".
Grimal advocates the change in the way classical music education is made, considering that "the work of musician, as it is organized today, has a death wish" and that "the future of music represents music itself".
We don't need to tour the world five times a year if it doesn't do any good.
In Bach's era there were no world tours.
Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were people who worked, who were artists and not commercial representatives.
For me, the organization of concerts, festivals, tours, album releases, they are all formidable, extraordinary, but as long as they are performed in the service of music.
If not, we are in a system where creativity suffers, it has no freedom.
To illustrate this phenomenon, David Grimal gave an example to Romanian products before and after joining the European Union: "In Romania, before entering the EU, you had good vegetables and meat".
To enter the EU you had to adopt health laws that are not good for vegetables and meat.
