On the occasion of the most expected meeting in recent years, policy makers within the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide whether the time has come to increase a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank meeting room, a United States mural will be seen.
The map is meant to recall that Janet L. Yellen, President of the Fed, and his colleagues must put the nation's economic interests above all else.
The Central Bank received a double task from Congress: to maximize the employment rate in the U.S. and maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in a decision too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the US economy is ready to be debated by the unprecedented incentive offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in effect as of late 2008.
Even though most of the data points to a strong growing economy, recent agitation in global financial markets could scare already cautious Fed officials from adding volatility by increasing the reference rate to federal funds - even by only a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main issues they will pursue," Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"I think, however, that if they were looking for an excuse not to increase the interest rate, the growing uncertainty on the world market is enough to give them arguments to wait," she said.
There is no consensus on the Fed's decision, which itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of economists recently questioned by Bloomberg anticipated an interest rate increase this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to postpone, with a key indicator showing that the probability of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a fall on the stock exchange if the Fed increases the interest rate, unless policymakers would mitigate the blow by promising that it would be a long time before the next increase.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The wind was triggered by expectations that Fed policy makers would keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be surprising for the Fed to raise the interest rate at this point," Lonski said.
If Fed makers were to do so, "they should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets".
Other experts said an increase in the interest rate would calm financial markets as it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be about to increase the rate by 0.25 percent this month, the first small step towards slowly tightening monetary conditions that would confirm the force of U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in spring and early summer that he expected an interest rate increase this year despite objections raised by liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth was strong this year.
The unemployment rate dropped to 5.1% last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years and close to the Fed's total employment.
Wage gains showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fail to reach the central bank's annual target, Fed decision-makers said that a key reason was the temporary effect of sharply declining oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tension in the labour market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to fibrillate later this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16% below the record peak reached in May, as investors feared that slowing down the Chinese economy would pull down world growth.
The market has somewhat recuperated this month, with the Dow index now being about 10% below its May peak.
For Fed policy makers, market agitation is added to the complex calculation of the moment of interest rate increase.
"Without what has happened in financial markets and news of the weakening of the Chinese economy in recent weeks, they would be more firm at the sitting," said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and former Fed official.
Now he predicts they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact on the US economy will be and they almost have no data to rely on after the events in China," said Oliner.
The welfare of the global economy is not one of the major interests of the Fed, so it should practically not be taken into account in decision making.
In reality, however, the Fed has become the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank's influence has been huge.
The mere allusion of the then President, Ben S. Bernanke, in 2013, that the Fed could "narrow" its monetary expansion triggered earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly linked, Fed officials are expected not only to monitor progress in other areas but also to consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
His decision-making process is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of the global strategy department at the welfare management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, President of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Va., said this month that "Fed has an oversized reaction history to changes in the financial market that appear to be unrelated to economic bases."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported the interest rate increase, provided as an example the 1998-99 decisions.
A financial crisis that affected Asia caused the Fed to reduce the reference rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "despite the implications with limited identification for US development," said Lacker.
A year later, Fed officials returned to their respective declines.
The Fed should only put financial stability first in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate setting committee.
The last hectic period is nowhere near rising to that level, he said.
"We certainly do not want to end up in a situation of fearing an increase in the interest rate because the markets were upset," said Posen, president of Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the double mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in that respect, I do not think it should take premature action.
