Weight reduction surgery could be useful for mildly obese diabetics
The benefits of weight reduction surgery for people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could be maintained for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say if mildly obese diabetics live longer after weight loss surgery than those who are undergoing non-surgical treatments.
"It takes a long time to centralize mortality data," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an obesity surgeon, which she wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, also referred to as bariatric surgery, use various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce hunger sensation and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted in people with morbid obesity with a 35 or higher body mass index (BMI).
BMI, a unit of weight measurement relative to height, is considered normal in the range 18.5-24.9.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used the data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes mellitus in people with mild obesity.
The mean BMI in people undergoing surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 to the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received non-surgical treatments against diabetes remained almost at the same level, namely 29.
Of those who underwent surgery, diabetes was completely cured at 36% and partly at 28%.
In the medically treated group, by comparison, diabetes was completely cured in only 1% and partly in just 2% of subjects.
Additionally, blood pressure control, triglycerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol "were generally better in the surgical group", the authors concluded.
Researchers also monitored the blood haemoglobin level of A1c, which reflects the blood glucose level over time.
Researchers write that the optimal A1c haemoglobin level is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean haemoglobin level of A1c decreased from approximately 9% to about 6%.
But in the medically treated group, it was maintained at about 8%.
But this improved "globe control" - reflected by improved levels of A1c hemoglobin - did not reduce the mortality rate to five years, according to chief researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the sleeve gastrectomy group, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), had more marked decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and A1c haemoglobin (3.1% versus 2.1%) and were more likely to have complete remission of diabetes (46.9% versus 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study conducted on high-weight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, Blackstone, of Arizona University, Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix says.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were approximately 29% less likely to die after 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in surgical patients, Blackstone said it was an optimistic aspect for people with BMI below 35 interested in the procedure.
"This is the point where this work is critical, because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group," without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking weight seriously then the patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
"I think we wait too long until we urge people to take this issue seriously," she said.
I think that once they have accumulated these genetic changes that have shorted out their bodies by predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it is extremely difficult to get back to normal.
