Movies that feature teenagers drinking detergent to create cheap drinks can be watched on YouTube.
The teenagers apparently mixed the detergent with mouthwash with alcohol to get a stronger drink.
Smaller children can be attracted by the attractive smell of detergent.
"A child doesn't think he's hurting her," says Lopez.
Many of the most attractive types (hand detergent) are those fragrant.
Strawberry, grape, orange-flavored hand cleaners are the most attractive to children.
Hand detergent contains approximately 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, only a few sips can cause alcohol poisoning.
"It's highly concentrated alcohol," said Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the anti-poison center at Kansas University Hospital, for channel Fox 4 in Kansas City.
Thus, we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand cleaners in accessible places and if the little ones reach them, this is a quick way to drink a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested at school the equivalent of four strawberry-flavored hand detergent sprays, arrived at the emergency room to receive treatment.
She had alcoholemia 179, twice the threshold at which an adult is legally considered under the influence of alcohol, according to Dr. Chris Ritchie, an emergency room physician who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
