The rare disease a man suffers from
American Nick Hess was suspected by his family of being an alcoholic, his wife even filming him when he was dizzy, he could barely stand up and his words were hard to understand.
Although the 35-year-old man said he didn't drink alcohol, he was clearly intoxicated.
When she first accused me of being drunk without drinking, I thought she was crazy.
"But friends and family believed 'maybe he drinks alone, he's an alcoholic in secret'," he recounts, according to the Mirror.
When he saw the footage of his wife with him, the man from Columbus, Ohio, he just didn't recognize himself: "I was looking into my eyes and I wasn't there".
'It was awful, I didn't remember anything.'
Plus, his wife, who, although she doubted him for a while, finally went with him to countless doctors, remembers that Nick's breath smelled like alcohol.
The moment that made Nick think most about it was when, after a minor accident, when he was hit by another car, it was discovered that he had a three-time alcohol level over the legal limit, although the night before he had only had one beer.
After years and innumerable investigations, it was discovered that Nick suffers from an extremely rare disease, Auto-brewery syndrome.
Basically, his body makes all the carbohydrates consumed ferment, turning into alcohol.
The one who suspected that this might be Nick's illness was even his wife.
The disease does not yet have a cure, but since he gave up carbs, Nick has not had such episodes.
