On Wednesday, the government approved the "National Immigration Strategy for 2015-2018" and the "Actuation Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "another stage Romania is undergoing in the framework of efforts to modernize the process of managing immigration on national territory", according to a press release.
The cited source shows that the strategy aims to effectively manage the immigration phenomenon, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and directions of action that reflect policies established at European level, adapted to national realities.
Given the problems faced by the states in the immediate vicinity of Romania, measures are envisaged for the unitary and coherent management of situations caused by the possible occurrence of an influx of illegal immigrants into Romania, generated by situations of political, social, economic or military crisis.
"The Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time, they will pay particular attention to citizens from states with potential migrationist or that may harm national security," added the source.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict situation in Syria, reactivating the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in areas bordering Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and increasing the intensity of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets out some general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, more rigorous controls of the legality of the residence of citizens of third states on Romanian territory and proper application of removal measures and restrictive measures, improvement of the national asylum system.
The national strategy also includes specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating the access to Romania of third-party citizens who respond to employment needs, facilitating the access of third-country nationals to higher education institutions in Romania for areas and professions identified as deficient.
Regarding the 2015 Action Plan, the Government appreciates that it is "a means by which concrete activities are established leading to the creation of a flexible system to stop the growing migrationist phenomenon".
Romania, in a European top on the labour market
Latvia, Romania and Bulgaria recorded the highest increase in the total labour cost of EU Member States in the second quarter of 2014 compared to the similar period, according to data published by the European Statistical Office (Eurostat) on Wednesday.
The index refers to employers' staff costs.
Thus, between April and June 2015, the total labour cost rose by 1.9% in the European Union and by 1.6% in the euro area.
Romania, third in the EU to increase labour costs
The largest increases were reported in Latvia (7.9%), Romania (7.7%), Bulgaria (6.8%), Estonia (5.5%) and Lithuania (4.3%).
The only EU countries where the hourly labour cost fell in the second quarter of this year were Greece (minus 2.9%), Cyprus (minus 1.2%) and Italy (minus 0.4%).
The advance of labour costs in Romania between April and June 2015 is mainly due to the increase of the hourly cost of labour in industry and services, by 7.9% and 7.6%, respectively.
In the construction sector, Romania registered a 5.8% advance on the hourly labour cost.
