What button's coming up soon?
Millions of Facebook users have become accustomed to the "Like" button, and now social networking representatives are preparing another opposite, the "Dislike" button.
Tuesday, Mark Zuckerberg, co-founder and executive director of the company, announced on his account that this button will be available soon, informs the New York Times on the blog.
Zuckerberg stated that the "Dislike" button would show a nuance of what a user feels rather than a simple option.
However, his announcement raised the issue that Facebook could become a less friendly place.
Zuckerberg mentioned that he wanted to avoid when someone was posting on his account an important event in life, and someone else was going to give "Dislike".
Users of the network, which reached 1.5 billion active accounts, have long called for the opportunity to express their negative emotions or empathy with something sad.
Mark Zuckerberg also said that it is not very comfortable for people to give "Like" to current events, such as the refugee crisis, or in the event of a death of a family member.
"You may not feel comfortable giving Like to that post," the Facebook representative pointed out.
The version of a new button on Facebook was not received well by everyone.
"There is already enough hatred on Facebook and social media," commented Atiq Haneef of Afghanistan, on the Facebook page of the New York Times, where the article was posted on the subject.
"I will give 'Dislike' to the 'Dislike' button," he said.
Roger Anderson, an Atlanta microbiologist, claimed there was nothing wrong with this button, encouraging people to have different views on Facebook.
Debra Aho Williamson, a social media analyst at eMarketer, mentioned that it is hard to imagine that a single button can transmit a complex range of negative emotions.
Moreover, she says, the election campaign is approaching in America, and the Dislike button would create a total disaster.
