EXCLUSIVE: A meeting that breaks your heart.
At the age of 20, he received a brave gift: biological parents
Lost in hospital in unclear conditions, in the black of the 1990s, when she had only two months of life, little, sick and helpless, and then adopted by a wealthy family in Italy, in the same years that the adoption was loosely regulated, a young woman from Ireland, now a blonde and beautiful girl, met again the other day in Iași with her biological parents from a village of the county, after almost two decades when no one knew anything about the others.
Crina will turn 20 these days, and her adoptive parents in Palermo thought to give their beloved daughter an amazing and courageous gift: a visit to Romania, to Iași, to get to know her unclear past.
"The Newspaper of Iași", which witnessed efforts to search for the family of origin after some extremely vague clues, witnessed these encounters that basically break your heart.
The story of the reporters, the emotions of the moments, the statements of those involved, their reactions are truly moving and overwhelming.
The story of Lily begins 20 years ago in the town of Ruginosa, when she was only two months old.
Then, because of a health problem, the girl had to be hospitalized in the city.
At home there began to be misunderstandings between parents, and the mother was forced to leave her home.
He decided to keep the girl and send me away.
He stopped the girl, and I haven't known anything since.
"When I found out she was in the hospital, it was too late," recalls grieving Alina, the girl's biological mother.
Crina was admitted with her grandmother to the municipal hospital in Pascani, and also then the girl's father, Costica Balcan, went to work in the city of Alexandria, Teleorman County.
Their lives would part forever.
They never found Crina at the hospital.
After internment, Lily's father went to work in another locality, and returned after six months.
Meanwhile, the girl was transferred to the hospital in Iași, and the father, when he returned, never found her.
I think it's been almost nine months since the girl was in the hospital.
"He must have thought it was abandoned," tells a niece of the family.
Due to financial problems, Grandma was unable to come with Crina to Iași, and the girl remained in the care of doctors.
Because no one took an interest in the fate of the child during this time, she was taken over by the General Directorate of Social Assistance and Child Protection Iasi, who then gave her up for care to the Placing Center in Bucium.
There were years when abandonment and adoption were more easily regulated than today in Romania.
At the Bucium Centre she was found by Italian Salvadore and his wife, a couple from Palermo who wanted to have their child but failed.
They fell in love instantly with blondie Crina, and after some time she would permanently move with them to Italy.
Little girl had already done almost two years, while the adoption formalities lasted.
When I saw Crina, I felt like she was our girl.
"As if my wife had given him life," Salvadore, the adoptive father, smiles at us, as he grabs the girl's thin hand.
In the country, Lily's parents, Alina and Costica, continued searching separately, each where they could.
The father asked the authorities in Rustinoasa, but received no answer as to where his child might be.
The police then told her that she might be dead, but in Iasi the parents found out what really happened to their daughter.
When I looked for her here, they told me in court she was away in Italy, in Palermo.
And the conditions to look for it were gone.
We prayed to God that he'd be all right.
I've been thinking about her for years, but there's been no possibility of us walking around, finding her.
"It's hard," tells us with tears in her eyes Lily's biological mother.
Even though the years passed, however, the parents of Ruginosa were not forgotten.
In Italy, Salvadore and his wife explained to the girl where she came from and that her past links her to Romania.
I was a little girl when I found out.
I guess I was five or six.
I reacted like a child, I was curious.
"I wanted to meet my parents in Romania," Crina says.
And her dream was about to come true.
In March of this year, Chief Romics Commissioner Ichim, director of the Regional Centre for Prevention, Evaluation and Drug Adviser Iași, was contacted by an acquaintance from Italy, who explained Salvadore's desire to find the biological family of the Lily.
And the search only came from a name.
After the request we had from our partners in Italy, we started the first steps.
I had just received a name, Balcan Costica, then the town, Ruginosa.
Soon I had an activity with the town hall there, and I could ask if there was a given name around the town.
Then they gave me a few directions, only the person they found wasn't the one they were looking for.
"It took about a month after that to find the girl's biological father," Chief Romics Commissioner Ichim explains.
In total, it took more than three months for the authorities to find Costica and Alina, especially since they were each domiciled in another locality.
We started our efforts somewhere in March, and in June-July we completed the identification of biological parents and discussions.
"Then we agreed that a first meeting would take place in September," Romică Ichim added.
In the past weekend, Alina and Costica first saw their lost girl in the halls of the hospital in Iasi, 20 years ago.
The father, excited, could barely contain his tears, and his hands trembled incessantly.
He barely talks to people around him.
A week before the meeting, he couldn't even sleep.
He was all excited, shaking.
"To see your child after so many years, it is something," says a niece, who also came with Costica from Ruginosa.
Meeting of the Lily with the biological mother and brother
In talks with his daughter, who is to study at a high-rated university in Italy, Costica Balcan told him, among other things, that if he once wanted to return to him, to the village, to come quietly: he can give him some sheep, goats, to find a boy from the village and raise a household.
My mom's excited too, she's crying, and she hardly thinks something like this can happen to her.
I'm very excited.
I never thought anything like this could happen.
I've seen cases like this on TV, I've been thinking these years, I've been hoping, but I didn't think I could be like that.
They're really great emotions.
If only he could forgive me.
I hope to visit you in the future.
"I hope we can keep a bond," tells us with great tears on Alina's cheeks, Lily's mother, while holding a napkin in her hand.
In him she hides her tears, from happiness, because soon she will see her face after so much bitter weather.
On the other side, Crina, who will be just a few days away, this month, 20 years old, tries to calm down like an emotional child.
She doesn't know what to expect, but she sketched a vague idea of her biological parents.
He thinks they're young, but now before the meeting he tries to gather his thoughts, because he has so much to say, but nothing to reproach.
My parents are two mothers and two fathers.
But my parents are the ones who raised me after all.
It'll be a nice meeting, a great experience.
"I hope I have a nice memory of them, because now there are so many things to say," Crina confesses.
First family meeting in Iasi
In Unirii Square, under the early autumn sky, the family of Ruginoasa again joins their destiny with their daughter from Palermo.
Crina is now 20 years old, finishing high school, following the Italian school model, but she can start a new chapter with Alina and Costica, her biological parents.
They no longer divide their borders or their countries, but only a barrier: that of the tongue.
Over which, with the help of a translator, an Italian local owner in central Iasi, they easily passed.
Those who have managed to make this meeting possible say that it is the first event of its kind made, and that in the future, if the opportunity arises again, they will do it again.
It is the first event of its kind organized, by such an emotional charge, and I am glad to be a success.
We, at the Centre, have different activities, and most of the time we are associated as an institution that deals only with consumers, people addicted to drugs.
But we're trying to give societies something good back.
"If I will be requested for such an event again, I will do it with great love," says Romică Ichim, director of the Regional Center for Prevention, Evaluation and Drug Advising Iasi.
Behind him, the Balcans, with Crina in the middle, drift away telling stories.
Understandably, they have a lot to say to each other.
