Corbyn, Brexit and the Future of Europe
Because of economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed over the last decades cannot continue the same in the years to come.
By Saturday probably few people knew in Romania who Jeremy Corbyn is.
Even today, after he has become the new leader of the Labour Party in Britain, many wonder to what extent we can affect the election of a politician who, after all, is not in a decision-making position.
Jeremy Corbyn is the most radical leftist leader of post-war Labour.
Marxist declared, anti-monarchist (he asked Tony Blair, then prime minister, to remove the royal family from Buckingam Palace), a fierce anti-American and sympathiser of Vladimir Putin (he was also regularly invited to comment on political events by the television channel "Russia Today"), and terrorist movements Hizbollah and Hamas, he wants Britain to give up nuclear weapons and get out of NATO and the EU.
For Corbyn, who at the time viewed Osama bin Laden as a real tragedy, ISIS is almost preferable to the United States.
According to the model of all populist demagogues, Corbyn has, of course, miraculous anti-austerity solutions.
Things like what Tsipras was saying and promising in Greece until he faced the real world and economic laws.
The economic programme of the new Labour leader provides, inter alia, for massive renationalisations and money printing as a solution for financing projects to develop and cover very generous social benefits.
Of course, some might wonder why the solution to printing money is not unanimously adopted around the globe, we would then have a general global prosperity!, but who would trip over such details.
Of course, we can tax bankers to blood, you become a sort of service enemies of the left, but from what has been seen so many times in the past, not only in the former communist states or in Ecuador or Venezuela, but also in France, at the beginning of Mitterand and Hollande's mandates.
Additional amounts are quickly swallowed by generous, uncovered promises made by populist demagogues.
As Margaret Thatcher well drew attention, "the problem with socialism is that at some point other people's money runs out."
Few give Jeremy Corbyn a real chance to ever become prime minister.
In the early 80s another radical left-wing leader, Michael Foot, who was anyway not as extreme in convictions as the party's fresh leader, failed miserably in the election.
And then there was still a working class in Britain, in the classical sense of the word, relatively consistent and structured.
And the unions were sensitively more influential than they are now.
Under the conditions of the new industrial landscape, in which services are dominant throughout the workforce, and extensive automations have caused a massive need for highly skilled labour in the industry, Corbyn's rhetoric has a limited appeal.
Even from opposition, however, it can influence important developments that can directly affect us.
In its latest Financial Times issue, Corbyn's choice increases the chances of Brexit and Britain's exit from the EU.
The new Labour leader was a consistent opponent of the country's membership in the Union.
In the eyes of the radical left Brussels is the agent of international capitalism and a promoter of globalisation that imposed austerity on the poor.
When you combine these kinds of ideas with those expressed by the radical right, with anti-immigration rhetoric, and you look at the refugee crisis that is shaking the EU to the ground, you get an explosive mix.
And not just for Britain.
But if the British decide following the referendum, which would take place by 2017, to leave the Union the loss of symbolic capital for the entire European project and the deep faults created within it by the Euro crisis and now that of refugees, between North and South, between East and West, leave room for the most worrying scenarios.
All the more so as for a whole series of Member States, London was a counterweight to the Franco-German axis (in which Berlin is becoming the dominant actor anyway).
It is true, the British business environment, the City, are strong lawyers of the country's stay in the EU.
But today's Europe is no longer the one of the past.
There are many resentments that are increasing in intensity these very weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, we have even recently had a sample in Jean Clude Junker's speech, is increasingly tending to make major decisions over the head of the large majority of Member States by consulting with only a few European powers, mainly with Germany.
And this happens as electoral support for anti-system, anti-immigration formations that are also Eurosceptics increases spectacularly across the continent.
In other words, the negative-loaded emotional climate has reached higher levels than ever in the past.
Hence the conclusion the Financial Times draws when assessing the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on a cold calculation based on national interest.
If voters make the brain decision, then Britain will remain in the EU.
But Corbyn's victory reminds us of the power of emotion in current politics.
However, Eastern Europe may be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as expected, we see a stronger integration of the Eurozone, which will push most of the countries in the region and the periphery of interest and the decision-making process in Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States fuels his populist rhetoric from frustrations accumulated in oocidental societies.
Because of economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed over the last decades, the generous social benefits, cannot continue the same in the coming years.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, the Euro-Immigration area, both caused by hasty decisions that have taken into account only integrationist political ambitions, not the ability and willingness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, the turbulence on the continent, the internal tensions in the EU will increase in intensity and can significantly affect Romania's situation.
And it's hard to exclude something from the point of view of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our main political leaders are able to deal with such complicated situations.
Constantin Brâncuși, the peasant god.
Rockefeller: "How can I help you?"
Brancusi: "Take and sweep the workshop!"
The great sculptor had a great dream: to be someone, to become famous, to be heard about him all over the world.
But behind his reputation lies something almost forgotten today, when millions of success stories are delivered, recipes for success in life.
That something also has a name.
It's called toil.
What to write about Constantin Brâncuși?
What more is there to say?
His face appeared on the bills.
And recently, a well-known Romanian bank hired an actor to play it in an advertising video.
Brâncuşi produces and delivers money almost 60 years since he is no longer with us.
In Romania, there are hundreds of streets and boulevards that bear his name.
