Brâncuși's life is the perfect counterexample.
And maybe here would be a key.
Maybe that's where the following text should start.
With a sentence, however detestable they are.
Forget the stupid success stories that are delivered to you every day in newspapers and on TV.
Take a good look at this man's face.
You want to know how he managed in life, how, today, did he hear an entire world?
It's simple.
He's worked his whole life to be someone.
That's what he did.
Constantin Brâncuși was born on 19 February 1876, in Hobita, a small village in Peștișani commune, Gorj County, at the foot of the Carpathians.
He is the fifth child of Maria and Radu Nicolae Brâncuși.
Although he came from a wealthy peasant family, Brâncuși leads a modest life, but one of which he would collect his landmarks that would guide his late artistic vision.
Remembering his childhood and the places where he grew up, the artist would confess, in a meeting with Petre Țutea, from Paris, 1933: "Life was then beautiful and harmonious".
For millennia, people led, happily, a patriarchal life.
Everything passed peacefully from one season to the next.
And do you know why things have changed?
The civilization of the great city has reached up to us.
Brâncuși's childhood, however, was far from an idyllic one.
One of the moments spent in these early years of life is extremely suggestive of the combination of purity and violence that characterized the future sculptor his years spent in his native locality.
The moment is reproduced in the work "Brâncuși. A biography", written by Alexandru Buican.
In 1879, Constantin Brâncuși was 3 years old.
In the autumn of that year, when the baby was made "at the boiler", watching those who taste the liquid to see if the process was proceeding properly, Brâncuși catches a moment of general inattention.
He fills his palms with jam and drinks out of breath.
He falls in his sleep almost instantly.
The first people don't notice until a few minutes later.
My mother panics, then goes into hysteria, thinking her son is dead.
In the evening, when the father, Radu, returns from the vineyard accompanied by fiddlers, he sees from a distance the desperate signs of those who are waiting for him with their breath.
The party immediately turns to mourning.
The father is already thinking of burial.
However, one finds that it is good to call Baba Brândusha, a doctor and a servant of the Brâncus.
Brandusa checks the baby's breath, then puts horse dung under his nose, gathered around.
The baby sneezes heavily.
People applaud.
While the boy is allowed to sleep on his drinking, for joy, the party with fiddlers continues with even more force.
The next day, the father and son meet through the orchard.
Radu Brâncuși has Constantine gather some rods and bring them to him.
The father places his child upside down and, with the rods brought by the boy, beats him to remember.
And as he feels the sting of the blows, little Brâncuși has the revelation that the world can also be viewed from another perspective and that things around him can appear overturned.
Especially the position of the sun, different from the one well known, makes him wonder, as he would admit in his old age, whether or not he himself was participating in his disorder.
Was the sun as troubled as his father by what had happened to him?.
